      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are facing a classic Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP), which is a mathematical challenge known to be extremely difficult to solve perfectly for large numbers of stops. For 12 stops, you can use a few strategies: manually map them on a whiteboard or use software like Google Maps or specialized route planning tools to simulate different orders. If you want the absolute best solution, consider using an online TSP solver where you input your addresses and let the algorithm calculate the most efficient path.\n\nJust remember that while algorithms are great, they don't account for real-world variables like traffic jams or delivery windows, so always double-check the route before the driver leaves. Sometimes, a slightly longer route that avoids a known traffic bottleneck might actually save more time and fuel than the mathematically \"perfect\" line.\n\nDid you mention if any of these deliveries have specific time restrictions? If so, the problem becomes much more complex, akin to the Vehicle Routing Problem with Time Windows (VRPTW), which is where you might need a dedicated logistics software or a human dispatcher to handle the complexity.\n\nAlso, have you considered asking the driver if they have any preferences for the order? Drivers are often experts in local traffic and may spot a better",
