    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to look for a heuristic or a simple rule of thumb, especially when you don't have time to run complex algorithms. For 12 stops without time windows, a great starting point is the **Nearest Neighbor** method: start at the warehouse, go to the closest delivery, then the next closest to that one, and so on, until you are forced to return to the start.\n\nHowever, since you are trying to save gas, you should be wary of the **Nearest Neighbor** algorithm because it can often result in a route that is only about 10-20% worse than the absolute best possible path. A slightly better manual approach is to divide the area into two or three zones based on the map, deliver all points in one zone before moving to the next, ensuring you don't zigzag back and forth across the city.\n\nIf you want to get even closer to the optimal solution without a computer, try the **2-opt** method manually: once you have a draft route, look for two segments of the route that cross each other like an 'X' and swap them to create a straighter line. Repeating this swap a few times usually saves significant fuel.\n\nJust",
      "source": "target",
